In the shadow of extinction: Three cheetah cubs were born in Iran.
The fastest animal in the world falls victim to cruel hunting, droughts, and deadly road accidents across the Islamic Republic.
As a result, their number dropped to less than 20 radars.
Three Asian cheetah cubs were recently born in the Islamic Republic of Iran.
This is a rare birth, which only slightly improves the tragic situation of the animal that is in danger of extinction in the country due to droughts, hunters, and deadly road accidents.
This is the first birth of a cheetah in captivity in Iran.
It should be noted that the Islamic Republic is one of the last countries in the world where cheetahs still live in the wild.
The Iranian news agency "IRNA" reported that the veterinary team, in charge of the Turan National Park in the northern Semnan province, decided on a cesarean birth for a captive animal.
It was also noted that recently less than 20 burglaries were recorded in seven different districts in the country.
Following the threat of their extinction, the UN implemented a protection plan for them back in 2001.
Now, in Iran, they hope that the new cubs will be able to contribute to the growth of the cheetah population in the future.
Last January, Iran's Deputy Minister for Environmental Affairs, Hassan Akbari, said that the country's cheetah population has dramatically decreased from 100 cheetahs in 2010 to just 12 cheetahs.
"Their situation is extremely severe," said the expert, noting that the turtles have fallen victim to drought in their habitats, hunting, and even road accidents.
The cheetah is considered the fastest animal in the world, capable of reaching speeds of approximately 100 km/h.
