Spotify wants to upgrade your car: We tested the Car Thing.
Quietly, Spotify has also started to try its luck in the hardware world.
After years of development - Car Thing was unveiled and launched as a small pilot in the USA.
We got our hands on the first device in Israel.
The vision: To turn your old cars into smart ones.
The Car Thing is Spotify's first hardware product, and it was specifically designed to provide a solution for people with older cars.
A few weeks ago, I got the first opportunity to try the new product, which is currently only available to a few testers in the US, here in Israel.
For me, the timing of the delivery was exceptional, as our family car broke down and we had to drive for a few days with a replacement car with an old system.
After two weeks of playing around, I understood how the Car Thing could easily become an integral part of many people's system.
On the other hand, with a long waiting list and uncertainty about the global launch, I believe many would prefer to use other solutions.
From concept to reality.
Somewhere in 2018, Spotify users started receiving an interesting offer in their email inbox - the opportunity to purchase a new device with voice control and 4G connectivity, which would turn any old car system into a smart one.
The rumors gradually died down until a year later, when the Financial Times revealed that the company plans to soon introduce a new car product that simulates a smart radio with Bluetooth connectivity.
A few months later, these rumors returned to the headlines after the music service updated with a car mode - the same one we know today from the app - activated when the smartphone detects a connection to the car system.
Two years have passed since then.
After countless rumors and leaks, Spotify revealed its smart car system, "Car Thing", last April.
Spotify chose to release the new device in a very limited way, with a long waiting list and many delays regarding deliveries.
So of course, immediately after the press conference she held, I went to the website and registered.
Two months later, the long-awaited message arrived.
Reconnecting to the site gave me the opportunity to purchase the device with a small surprise - it won't cost me anything.
After another month of waiting, the courier finally knocked on my door, accompanied by a small box with the Spotify logo on it.
The Car Thing
First and foremost, I was very impressed by the build quality of Spotify's device.
It's slightly smaller than my iPhone 11 and features a large, bright, and sharp touch screen on the front.
Also, next to the screen, you can find a round button and a dial that you can rotate to navigate through the interface screens.
Despite the huge dial, which you can see in the pictures, the Car Thing manages to maintain a relatively slim profile and not protrude too much from the dashboard.
Personally, I would prefer if the company allowed to change the dial function so I could control the smartphone's volume, as I can also navigate using the touch screen.
Maybe it will be possible in a future version update.
The device comes in a small, minimalist cardboard box, which includes among other things a USB Type C cable and various adapters for its installation.
Many of you probably remember how in the past we used to disconnect the radio devices and hide them in the drawer after leaving the car.
The Car Thing definitely brings back that feeling with its construction.
All the adapters were connected to the device body using a very strong magnet, which prevented it from falling even when driving on dirt roads.
In addition, along its top part, you can find small buttons, which can be easily set to play different playlists or podcasts.
By long pressing one of the buttons during playback, or by asking the voice assistant, I set up several playlists that I listen to frequently and the radio program that I listen to every morning on the road.
In doing so, the feature made me feel like the Car Thing is more like a car radio rather than an extension of my smartphone.
From an old vehicle to a smart car.
After a simple physical installation, I connected the Car Thing to the power.
I was pleasantly surprised by the setup process.
The instructions were clear, connecting to the Spotify app took less than 5 minutes, and a few moments later I reached the home screen.
In fact, the device connects to the smartphone via Bluetooth and controls the app like a remote, therefore it can copy all the information about our account.
Meaning, you will still need to connect your smartphone to the car, whether via Bluetooth or an AUX cable, in order to listen to the music.
The home screen is familiar to all app users, as like the smartphone application, it emphasizes album pictures and playlists.
Also, on the home screen, like in the app, you can find music recommendations according to your taste, the search screen, and your personal library.
As mentioned, you can navigate between the different screens using the touch screen or the manual dial.
Moreover, at any given moment, you can call the device's voice assistant by saying "Hey Spotify".
With it, you can play songs, playlists, albums and even search for podcasts.
From my experience, it easily recognized my voice even when music was playing in the background and the air conditioner was blowing directly on the device.
This is probably thanks to the four microphones installed in its upper part.
It's important to note that currently the voice assistant does not support Hebrew, and as of the time of publishing this article, there is no information on when such an update will arrive.
So, is it worth waiting for him?
My user experience with the device was great, and it was a positive surprise for me considering it is still in its initial release stage.
Even with intensive use on long trips, the device continued to work smoothly without disconnecting from my smartphone.
Nevertheless, occasionally there is a minor glitch in the interface, but I believe that Spotify will address such bugs with future version updates.
It's clear that the Swedish company has worked a lot on it in recent years, and among the various versions that leaked on the internet during this period, the design of the final product is probably my favorite.
Still, when I first saw the Car Thing, I wondered exactly who the company was trying to target with it.
After all, his activity is summed up in controlling the application on the smartphone, and not much beyond that.
What's the difference between buying a car mount for a few shekels and connecting it so that the smartphone is closer to us while driving?
This question becomes stronger when considering that iPhone and Android devices are much more powerful than Spotify's, and most of the time they will provide the user with much more functionality.
Despite all this, the more I used the Car Thing, the more I understood how it could improve the driving experience.
The ability to see Waze on my smartphone screen and control the music on a completely different screen is something I've come to appreciate in the last two weeks.
One question remains - will Spotify even launch the device to the general public?
So, will it also be launched here in our small country?
The Swedish company is not currently saying much.
She didn't even share how many trials for the device she is currently running worldwide, and how many she plans to add in the limited launch in the United States.
The only thing we know for sure is that the price is expected to be 79 dollars (about 255 shekels).
Meanwhile, the Car Thing provides a first glimpse into the concept that Spotify has been trying to crack for years.
From Spotify Israel it was reported that there is currently no information about a plan to launch the device in the country.
