Did you recruit talent for the company?
This way you will ensure that competitors do not "snatch" it from you.
The economy is still in a labor market that is mostly controlled by the workers, and this is especially true when it comes to the most sought-after workers - the talents.
Here are some tips that will help you maintain it at the workplace.
.
Despite the increase recorded in the last month, the unemployment rate in Israel continues to be one of the lowest in the world, and in the top tenth among OECD countries, with a rate of 3.5% (150.6 thousand unemployed, according to the CBS).
In other words, the economy is still in a labor market that is mostly controlled by the workers, and this is especially true when it comes to the most sought-after workers - the talents.
Regarding those professionals and managers who are centers of knowledge, experience, and proven ability - the trends in the job market indicate that the competition for them, the talents as they are called by employers, still exists in full force.
The implication for employers is that in the current job market, they do not have the luxury of resting on their laurels even for a minute after recruiting a desired talent, as the moment he enters the company's gates - another company will already try to snatch him away.
In other words, the competition for talents is so fierce that many will continue to receive a variety of tempting job offers even after they have been hired, with 30% of employees indeed leaving just a month after accepting the job and starting work.
That's why smart employers will immediately transition from the talent recruitment stage to its retention stage, starting primarily with advanced preparation and creativity already in the onboarding process.
An efficient, thoughtful and well-structured onboarding process will make the talent excited about their new workplace from the first day and even look forward to the future.
Here are some tips on how to prepare and manage a proper onboarding process that will help retain the new talent:
It's no secret - the organization's collaboration and readiness.
Share with the stakeholders who will work with him on his recruitment, explain to them why he is vital and important to the company and the role, and how you see his contribution.
A new employee who arrives at a place where he is expected and his value is understood, will feel wanted and will strive to meet the expectations placed on him.
Knowledge is power - coordinating expectations.
On the first day, they had an expectation coordination conversation with the talent.
Get to know his professional background and check where he sees himself in the future, so you can present him with the diverse and unique tools that you and the workplace can provide him to get there.
We are all people - Personal acquaintance |
During the onboarding days, they tried to get to know the talent beyond his professional qualities and were interested in his hobbies and areas of interest.
A new employee who is shown interest and allowed to express and realize himself beyond his role will appreciate it and want to maintain it.
Curiosity promotes |
Already at the recruitment stage, you can create attractiveness that will make the talent want to integrate quickly.
They did this not necessarily through a discourse of bonuses and benefits, but by exposing him to an exciting field or interesting technology, as such stimuli for creativity lead to curiosity and increased interest in the workplace.
Also, they encouraged the talent to voice his thoughts and opinions on the various projects in the company, making it clear that they are important to the organization.
The author is the CEO of Manpower Israel - the largest recruitment and human resources company in Israel.
Electricity in the pocket: The cost of not closing the coal plants in June - one billion shekels.
A report from the Knesset's Research and Information Center: The estimated cost of not closing the coal stations by the set date in June 2022 is about one billion shekels.
The Electric Company: "The policy of fuel usage is primarily dictated by the Ministry of Energy."
.
The economic cost of not closing the coal stations by the set date in June 2022 is estimated at about one billion shekels for the year 2022, as revealed by a report from the Research and Information Center of the Knesset.
According to the report, this cost is reflected in the electricity tariff for consumers, which is expected to rise in the coming months due to the increase in coal prices.
In addition, in 2023, there is expected to be an additional surplus of about 900,000 tons of coal usage, which will result in additional costs to the electricity market due to the non-closure of coal plants, assuming that the price of natural gas will remain significantly lower than the price of coal.
The report stated that a reduction of about one billion shekels in the electricity tariff in 2022 would mean a reduction of about 4% in the electricity consumption tariff for the domestic consumer.
In other words, the economic cost of not closing the stations is about a billion shekels, and the total discount that could have been for the domestic consumer is about 4%.
It should be noted that as part of the electricity market reform, among other things, it was decided to establish a subsidiary of the Electric Company, which will build units powered by natural gas, intended to replace coal units 1-4 at the Orot Rabin site.
Following this decision, a government resolution was adopted in July 2018, stating that the operation of coal production units 1-4 at the Orot Rabin power station should be ceased.
The decision set timelines, so the construction of the first natural gas unit will begin in January 2020 and its operation will start in June 2022, and accordingly, the coal production units 1-4 will also cease to operate at this time.
The Electric Company responded: "The policy of fuel usage is primarily dictated by the Ministry of Energy.
In accordance with the ministry's decisions, a policy of minimizing the use of coal to the lowest possible level has been implemented in Israel for several years, even when the price of coal is lower than the price of gas.
Paying the price: Everything you need to know ahead of the interest rate hike.
Continuous cuts: Next week, the interest rate on the shekel is expected to rise by half a percent.
How much will the mortgage payment increase?
And what is recommended to do? •
All the answers.
The sharp inflation in Israel, which has already reached a rate of over 4% in the last year, will force the Bank of Israel to raise the interest rate on the shekel as early as next week.
The analysts' estimates talk about an increase rate ranging between 0.25% to 0.5%.
If indeed the interest rate increases by half a percent, it will already stand at 1.25%, the highest level in nine years.
This, after for years the interest rate in the economy was close to zero.
The sharp increase in the interest rate significantly raises the mortgage repayments by hundreds of shekels and drastically burdens the household economy.
With the help of Shai Tzror, a mortgage expert, we checked how much more we will pay and what is recommended to do right now.
If the interest rate increases by half a percent - how much will the monthly mortgage payment increase?
In a mortgage of 1.2 million shekels, composed of 40% prime interest rate, the monthly repayment will increase by 125 shekels.
How much has the average mortgage increased since the beginning of the year?
Since the beginning of the year, there has been a significantly sharper increase.
This is because the interest rates in the other mortgage components (not just in the prime track) have also increased - in the index-linked track and in the fixed interest rate track.
If the interest rate indeed rises by half a percent, the increase will amount to about 620 shekels, according to Tzror's estimate, on a mortgage of about 1.2 million shekels.
The Prime track (40% in this track) will complete an increase of about 280 shekels, assuming there will be another 0.5% increase next month.
The variable interest rate track linked to the index (26.7% in this track) will complete an increase of about 120 shekels.
The fixed interest rate track - not linked to the index (33.3% in this track) will increase by 220 shekels.
So what is recommended to do today?
For those who have a mortgage that is mostly linked to the index, Tsror recommends considering recycling to non-linked tracks.
For those with mortgages who find their monthly repayments have significantly increased and are struggling to meet them - he recommends considering a mortgage recycling and spreading it over a longer period.
This is to reduce the payments despite the interest rate increase, as it is always better to meet the repayments and not to be in default.
Regarding new mortgage borrowers - he highly recommends getting to know the different paths and adjusting the mortgage to their economic capabilities.
In the future, when the interest rates drop, they will be able to refinance their mortgage with minimal early repayment fees.
Regarding those who purchase apartments from a contractor - Tzror recommends making payments to the contractor in advance and taking a mortgage now.
It should be taken into account that the "construction inputs index" significantly increases the property price even after the purchase contract has been signed.
The residential construction cost index has risen by 6.6% in the last year.
In light of the increase in this index, the Banking Supervision recently announced that it is considering requiring the inclusion of indexation within mortgages, however, the final decision on the matter has not yet been made.
The fuel price is rising - and Israelis will have to pay more than 8 shekels per liter in July.
The Ministry of Energy announced that the new price for a liter of 95 octane gasoline will be 8.08 shekels.
Meanwhile, the reduction of half a shekel per liter in the diesel tax will be extended until the end of 2022.
Decade high: The price of gasoline will jump by 36 cents per liter - and will stand from July 1st at more than 8 shekels per liter.
The new price for a liter of 95 octane gasoline will be 8.08, and those who want full service will have to pay an additional 21 agorot per liter.
Simultaneously, the reduction of half a shekel per liter in the diesel tax will be extended until the end of 2022 - as announced by the Tax Authority.
As mentioned, the price increase is due to the continued rise in oil prices, against the backdrop of the war between Russia and Ukraine and the rise of the dollar.
Without the half shekel subsidy from the government since April, the fuel price would have exceeded the all-time high - 8.25 shekels per liter.
The validity of the discount ends at the end of July and the Tax Authority and the Treasury are currently promoting a public notice of the order extending the reduction in gasoline tax, which stands at half a shekel per liter, until August 9.
Also, starting from August 10th, there will be an additional reduction of half a shekel, so only from this date the price of a liter of gasoline will decrease by one shekel until November 15th, 2022.
This was announced by the Tax Authority.
"We have reached a situation where I can't remember five consecutive months of surplus in the state's revenue.
We started a few months ago with the issue of reducing the tax on diesel.
We have been working for a week on extending the tax on diesel, gasoline and blue fuel for another four months - from half a shekel to a shekel.
It's good for the industry and the citizen.
If we lower it, it will affect inflation, reduce production and ease the cost of living.
"The Finance Minister, despite the election campaign, I intend to focus primarily on this," said Minister Liberman at the Horowitz Conference for Economy and Society of the Israel Democracy Institute.
As of today, more than half of the fuel price is the taxes collected by the government (excise tax and VAT) - and this is a high tax rate compared to most developed countries.
The price of fuel has a dramatic impact on the cost of living in the economy - as it affects both household expenses and business expenses, public transportation and flight prices, transportation costs and more.
For the third time in a row: Ashdod - the most business-friendly city.
Petah Tikva reached second place in the business conduct rating of the Ministry of Economy.
Following them: Rehovot, Ashkelon and Rishon LeZion.
Minister Barvivai: "The Corona emphasized the importance of local government in business development."
.
Ashdod is the most business-friendly city for small and medium-sized businesses.
This is the third consecutive year - as found by the Doing Business Index of Local Authorities by the Small and Medium Business Agency in the Ministry of Economy and Industry, which ranks the local authorities.
In second place is the city of Petah Tikva and in third place is Rehovot.
Following them in order are: Ashkelon, Rishon LeZion, Tel Aviv-Yafo, Haifa, Ramat Gan, Holon, Be'er Sheva, Jerusalem, Bat Yam, Netanya, and Bnei Brak.
The agency compiles the local authorities index.
This is the fifth time and its purpose is to serve as a tool for the local authority, as it allows each authority to compare its performance with other authorities in a variety of parameters, and also to analyze its performance in the areas in which it operates.
The index is based on several parameters that are examined in each authority, which assess the "friendliness" level of the authority to the businesses operating in its area.
The index divides the authorities into three size groups according to the number of residents, as a local authority of up to 50,000 residents is not similar to a local authority of more than 150,000 residents.
This year, Tel Aviv has jumped.
The index is updated once a year and weighs four different ratings in each local authority: business satisfaction, tender accessibility, information accessibility, and property tax.
From the ranking, it appears that Ramat Gan has dropped from second to eighth place, Bat Yam has dropped from fourth to twelfth place, and Netanya has dropped from fifth to thirteenth place.
A decrease in rating does not mean that the authority's business service has deteriorated, and in many cases it is due to the fact that the service of other authorities to businesses has improved more and they have risen in the rating, while the authority that has dropped in rating has improved its services to businesses less.
Among the cities that have risen in the ranking, one can find Petah Tikva, which has moved from sixth to second place, and Rehovot, which has moved from twelfth to third place.
Tel Aviv, which dropped from fourth place to eleventh in 2019, improved in 2021 and rose to sixth place.
"Business - The Engine of Growth"
From the ranking, it appears that the Galilee Panorama leads among local authorities that include between 50 and 150 thousand residents.
Following it are Kiryat Motzkin, Mateh Binyamin, Modi'in-Maccabim-Re'ut, Kfar Saba, Ra'anana, Nahariya, Karmiel, Afula, and Hod Hasharon.
Tiberias is ranked in the last and 28th place.
"The index is designed to encourage local authorities to ease the burden on small and medium businesses, from the time of opening the business and throughout its operation with the authorities," says Minister of Economy and Industry, Orna Barbivai.
"Businesses are a significant growth engine for the Israeli economy and they account for about 50% of the business output and about 60% of the employees in the economy.
The development of small businesses is a public interest for all of us, however, the local authority has a direct influence on the businesses located within it.
The Corona emphasized the importance of local government and we saw that authorities that acted and encouraged the promotion of small businesses and found creative solutions for them, became their first governmental interface.
Ran Kiviti, the director of the Small and Medium Business Agency at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, adds: "Local authorities play a central and substantial role in the ability of businesses in their jurisdiction to thrive and prosper."
In the last two years, in which we are dealing with the Corona crisis, the authorities have a greater responsibility in helping businesses to survive in their field and to survive in general.
2021 in mail: 20 packages for each household - and a surge in their weight.
46.6 million packages arrived in Israel during 2021 - similar to 2020.
The average weight of a package stands at 435 grams - a jump of 36% compared to 2020.
The busiest month: December, when the average package weight stood at 524 grams.
In 2021, 46.6 million mail packages arrived in Israel, almost 20 packages on average for each household - according to data from Israel Post that reached "Israel Today".
The number of packages that arrived in 2021 is similar to 2020, in which 46.5 million packages arrived in Israel, and lower than 2019 - when 61.6 million packages arrived.
However, this year there was a jump of more than 36% in the weight of packages arriving from abroad.
In 2021, 20,253 tons of products arrived in Israel from abroad, a jump of 36% compared to 14,860 tons in 2020, and 16,743 tons in 2019.
Changes in consumption habits.
The average weight of a package jumped by 60% in two years - from 272 grams in 2019 to 435 grams in 2021.
The increase in package weight is mainly influenced by two central trends, both from the seller and the buyer's side: large shopping sites abroad are combining items into one shipment and no longer send each product from the "shopping basket" in separate packaging.
From the Israeli consumer's perspective, the fast delivery of orders, within a few days from the moment of purchase, supports the buying of more everyday items such as clothing and gifts, which buyers want to receive shortly after making the purchase.
Also in 2021, as in 2020 and 2019, the month in which the most packages from abroad arrived, both in terms of weight and number of items, was December, with 4.2 million packages weighing a total of 2,200 tons.
In December, the average weight per package was 524 grams, 20% higher than the annual average weight.
Black Friday effect.
More packages arrived in December than any other month, likely due to the shopping holidays in November, such as Chinese Singles Day, Black Friday, and Cyber Monday.
The large orders start to arrive in Israel between a week to two weeks after the purchase.
Research: Most employees in the economy are not aware that they can receive tax refunds.
Many renters receive money from the state, which can amount to tens of thousands of shekels.
Did you change your workplace?
Did you go on vacation?
Did you move from the city to the settlement?
You may be entitled to receive a substantial amount through a simple process.
All the details - inside.
Most renters are not aware of the fact that they are entitled to tax refunds, which can accumulate to high amounts.
The State Comptroller noted in a report two months ago that two million employees are entitled to tax refunds amounting to 3.6 billion shekels, which means it's worth checking if you are also entitled to a tax refund.
Many employees can receive a high amount, as four out of five employees are eligible for tax refunds.
In practice, however, tens of thousands of employees submit annually.
If you think that this money has already gone down the drain, think again: renters can apply to the income tax for refunds for up to six years back.
Tax:On company conducted an in-depth research among 4,000 of its customers regarding tax returns during 2020.
The company has over 30,000 customers, so the sample reflects their distribution in terms of population groups, gender, age, and geography.
The data shows that during 2020, due to the outbreak of the Corona crisis and the furlough of hundreds of thousands of workers, several significant changes occurred, central among them a 15% increase in the average refund to a household, which stood at 4,300 shekels a year.
The reason is that the severance pay is lower than the salaries, therefore a gap is created between what the employee paid as tax and what he actually needs.
By the way, the highest refund received by a customer of the company in 2020 was an amount of 121,054 NIS for refunds over the last 6 years.
What can you get tax refunds for?
One of the reasons to get a tax refund is a change in the workplace.
81% of people who changed jobs during the year received a tax refund with an average amount of 2,943 shekels.
Another reason is maternity leave.
The data shows that 74% of women who gave birth and took more than 16 weeks of maternity leave were eligible for an average refund of 3,538 shekels for that year.
Another reason for the refund is donations.
100% of the people who donate and pay taxes received a refund.
Another reason for the refund is the non-registration of credit points for alimony. 63%
The divorcees did not update the credit point for alimony, therefore the tax refund for each year that such a credit point was not updated is 2,616 shekels.
Due to unemployment - tax refund: 93% of those who were unemployed or on leave and earned over 12,000 shekels received a tax refund of 4,021 shekels for that year.
Other reasons for tax refunds include: refunds for life insurance payments, mortgage life insurance, settlement refund, refunds for losses in securities, non-registration of credit points for men due to birth, and distribution of tax refunds according to geographical location.
94% of people who have taken out personal life insurance or a mortgage were eligible for a tax refund.
In a test conducted on a million shekel mortgage for 25 years, the accumulated tax return for the period is over 20,000 shekels for the entire mortgage period.
100% of the people who moved to the eligible settlement received a tax refund for the transition year, as the residency confirmation in the eligible settlement is only given after 12 months from the day the resident becomes eligible, thus in fact, the full tax is paid in the first year.
79% of the customers holding securities were eligible for a tax refund for the said years.
However, those who hold securities should check every year as losses are not rolled over from year to year, but only through filing a report.
56% of men who have a child do not register credit points in the birth year on their pay slip.
The refund rate can reach tens of thousands of shekels over 6 years.
This is a phenomenon that mainly exists in the Arab sector.
The CEO of tax:on, Tal Carmon: "The Corona crisis has made the renters' public in Israel much more active."
He is interested, checks and demands what he is entitled to in income tax returns.
It turns out that staying at home, on unpaid leave or after being fired, for many months, has led many employees to deeply examine what they are entitled to from the state.
It's important to know that today all the procedures for getting tax refunds can be done digitally, easily and simply, without the bureaucracy that deterred many in the past.
Job market: Fewer candidates for a position, higher salary.
Oljobs' 2021 summary report: At the top of the demands - jobs without experience.
The volume of jobs offered increased by 50%.
"Looking for work, but not rushing into the market"
In the past year, there was a 15% decrease in the number of resumes sent, and only an average of 23 candidates competed for each position, compared to 41 candidates in the previous year - according to a report by AllJobs website summarizing 2021, on the Corona crisis and its effects on the job market in Israel.
According to the report, job seekers were mainly interested in fields with many positions such as administration and sales, for which 1,738,485 resumes were sent.
However, the jobs without experience led the demand with more than 38 thousand searches - probably due to the return of young people without professional experience looking for immediate work, after the end of unemployment benefits.
The number of searches for sales and administration was 35 thousand and 32 thousand respectively, for drivers and couriers there were 11 thousand searches, and for security there were slightly less than 9,000 searches.
On the other hand, despite the Corona crisis, the salary in 2021 increased by 2% compared to 2020, and the average salary in Israel was 11,675 shekels gross.
The average monthly salary in the software field was 17,915 shekels, and in information systems analysis, it was 17,140 shekels.
However, there was a wage gap of more than 2,000 shekels between the center and the periphery: in the center of the country it was an average of 12,500 shekels, compared to 10,795 in the north and 10,135 shekels in the south.
From a gender perspective, the average wage gap between women and men, which can also be explained by the type of work and the number of hours, remained at 36%.
Men earned 13,295 shekels, compared to women's wages which stood at 9,740 shekels.
Trying to get back on track.
On the business side, there was almost across-the-board growth in all sectors of the economy, and businesses were desperate for workers.
Thus, the job supply increased by 50% and recorded a record of more than 40,000 jobs on AllJobs.
A survey conducted by the site among employers found that 50% were optimistic about their economic status in 2022, 30% of them indicated their intention to increase the total recruitments but 72% understand that they will struggle with it this year.
The largest supply was for jobs without experience - there were more than 58 thousand on the site.
Following them were customer service and administration roles with about 44,000 jobs in each field, sales and software with 41,000 jobs each, teaching and education with 24,000 available jobs, and warehouse workers are still in demand with 19,000 available jobs.
Einav Boimfeld, the research and content manager at AllJobs: "Job seekers are trying to get back on track but they are not rushing into the market, mainly due to the lack of attractive positions in their eyes.
Also, the prolonged disconnection from the work cycle makes it difficult for them to return, and some of them have found creative ways to make a living.
The CBS: Unemployment rate in Israel has risen to 6.3%
According to the Bureau's survey, about 270,000 Israelis remained unemployed in December 2021.
In November, there were about 262 thousand unemployed.
The unemployment rate in the first half of December 2021 stood at 6.3%, about 270,000 Israelis, compared to 6.1% in the second half of November 2021 (about 262,000).
This is according to the manpower survey data for the first half of December 2021 by the Central Bureau of Statistics.
The unemployment rate stood at 4.5% in the first half of December 2021 compared to 4.3% in the second half of November 2021.
In other words, it's 193 thousand unemployed versus 180.3 thousand.
According to the labor force characteristics in the first half of December 2021 among those aged 15 and above, it appears that this population included 6,607,500 residents in Israel, not including institutions and residents outside of settlements.
Out of them, 64.4%, which is 4,252,700, are in the workforce and the rest, which is 2,354,800, are not in the workforce.
Of those who are able to work, 95.5% which constitutes 4,059,700 are employed and the rest are unemployed.
Of those who are not employed, 2.3% stopped working due to layoffs or job closure since March 2020.
The labor force survey provides information about the workforce in Israel and is conducted regularly by the Central Bureau of Statistics.
In the first half of December 2021, we continuously interviewed about 8,700 people aged 15 and above.
In the second half of November 2021, we continuously interviewed about 8,900 people aged 15 and above.
The survey population includes the permanent residents of Israel, tourists and temporary residents who have been staying in Israel for more than a year consecutively.
The survey allows tracking the development of the workforce, its size and characteristics, the extent of unemployment, and more.
"Taken for granted": Subliminal sanctifies the Sabbath - and prepares for independence.
Celebrates the fact that "we can live as we please", excited to meet the audience and makes sure to spend time with the kids.
The weekend and Independence Day by Kobi Shimon, Subliminal.
What does your typical Friday look like?
"Weekends are the most important moments in my life, from my perspective."
The sanctity and tradition are a very deep root in my soul.
Fridays at my place are dedicated to my children, Or (10) and Yonatan (8).
I pick them up from school, we buy flowers and supplies for the Kiddush, eat lunch and do something fun together, like playing football, horse riding or playing with remote control cars.
Sometimes we go to the sea, or even just to wash the car, but we always stop on the way to buy a gift at the neighborhood toy store - and there's always another excuse.
When we return home with all the gifts, the smells of the cooking greet us.
What does your Friday meal look like?
"I am blessed with maturity around me."
On my side, there is a Persian-Tunisian kitchen, full of salads and an atmosphere of laughter, music, singing and joy.
From my wife Ines, who is also a great cook, come the Ukrainian dishes, which are deep and spicy, with a lot of meat.
When we arrive at my mother-in-law's, amazing smells are already wafting up from her apartment in the building.
Usually, I do the Kiddush, along with the children, who know it by heart.
At the end of the day, my fun after eating is to collapse on the rug, and the kids jump on me as if I'm some kind of inflatable.
Do you have a special childhood memory from the weekends?
"As a child, I would wake up on Saturdays to the sounds of Israeli music on Channel 3 and the skits of 'The Pale Tracker', which we knew by heart.
My father loved nature and we traveled a lot in Israel, usually to the north.
Every neglected corner in the country filled his heart with pride.
He passed away three months ago from a severe illness, and for him, the Sabbath and the sanctification were the holiest of holies, mainly because the whole family should be together.
Recently, I released a song in his memory called 'Shomer Alecha', which I created with Osher Cohen.
I believe he would be proud of this creation, which sanctifies the bond between father and son."
Soon we will celebrate the 74th Independence Day. As an ardent Zionist, what are your feelings about the holiday?
"Independence Day is a sacred day for me, and part of my meaning and identity.
In Persia and Tunisia, my parents had to hide their Jewish identity, while I am an Israeli Jew who is privileged to live with his children in our country.
A week or two before Independence Day, I was already climbing trees and tying Israeli flags to the house with strings.
My Independence Days are filled with performances, and I always meet an ecstatic crowd, celebrating the fact that we can live as we please.
We need to ensure that our children, grandchildren, and great-grandchildren also have this opportunity, and remember that nothing here is taken for granted."
Her Friday: Esti Zakheim welcomes the Sabbath.
"My dream is to set a big table and invite all my beloved deceased": This is the Friday dinner that Esti Zakheim dreams of, and how does she cope with the fact that her husband observes Shabbath?
Tell me about your preparations for Shabbat.
.
"The preparations start already on Thursday night, when I come back from a show or workshop and cook until three in the morning everything that requires long cooking like stew, roast and sauces."
On Friday, in the first part of the day, I dedicate my time to myself, meeting friends for coffee, going to a play or a movie, or participating in rehearsals.
In the summer, the Sabbath starts late, and I have plenty of time to sit in the neighborhood garden and watch the sunset or just a good series.
During the Sabbath meal, I usually host my mother, Vered, who just turned 89, and also friends.
Can you share more about the cooking?
"I love shortcuts.
For example, instead of peeling 10 onions, cutting and crying, I buy a bag of frozen onions and fry them.
On my Sabbath table, you can find meat dishes, vegan tofu dishes, baked potatoes and cauliflower.
I prepare most of the dishes, and of course, they are warmed up on the hotplate on Shabbat.
Alejandro, my partner, makes chicken soup, vegetable salad and in winter - the "cholent".
Your husband is religious and you come from a secular home.
How does it work?
"Living with someone who observes Shabbat is an endless compromise.
'Love your neighbor as yourself', a practical commandment.
He can't go on family trips, so I found myself many times packing the kids and joining my friends' family trips.
In addition, I am also the designated driver for the kids, the one who picks them up on Friday nights from parties and gatherings.
On the other hand, I also enjoy the benefits of his Sabbath, because I usually don't work on Saturdays and get a kind of 'forced vacation' - and that's a good thing.
Who would you like to host for Shabbat?
"I would set a big table and invite 'my dead ones'.
Sometimes I imagine what it would be like if my brother Daniel, may he rest in peace, was alive, or if my father, Shneor, may he rest in peace, could see my children: Uriel (23) and the twins Tamara and Naama (16 and a half).
We surely argued a lot about football and politics and were amazed at each other.
Do you have a special childhood memory from the weekends?
"We were a warm and united family."
On Friday afternoon, mom would make a pile of schnitzels, bring hummus and pitas from the market, and roast eggplants for tahini salad.
Afterwards, we would travel to Aunt Hannah in Yad Eliyahu, or as she would say 'Yad Eliyake', and she would make blintzes.
Since I was the only one who didn't like raisins, she would make some without raisins for me.
She saw me, the youngest of the siblings, and took care of me.
On Saturdays, we would take a tour with my father in Jaffa port, and he would show us where he and his brother, Grisha, arrived in the country with nothing.
