During his visit to the country, Kaye told the local media: "Ultimately, I am here for two reasons: the first reason is because I love Israel and the Israelis, and the second reason is that I am against anyone who tries to censor and silence musicians."
The same Achmat vividly remembered Kiev's statements in favor of music and against politicization.
The fan even published on the singer's personal and uncensored website, "The Red Hand Files", a pointed post in which he claimed that Israel is also an occupying country, therefore Palestine's situation is identical to Ukraine's.
"What bothers me about your statement on Ukraine," wrote Achmet, "is that you didn't similarly support the Palestinians, who are also suffering from a brutal regime."
In fact, you described Israel as a functioning democracy, but in my opinion, Israel is primarily the party responsible for the Palestinian suffering.
"It saddens me a lot, because you represent a double standard here," concluded the Turkish fan.
But the story doesn't end here, as Kyiv chose to respond to Achmat with a long and detailed letter, emphasizing that "Russia's invasion of Ukraine is very different from the ongoing conflict between Israel and the Palestinians.
The first scenario is an unprovoked attack by one country on its neighbor, in the hope of changing the entire security order of Europe.
The second situation is a complex conflict between two nations.
The conflicts are similar in that innocent people, who share a tragic fate, are forced to hide in shelters.
I feel a lot of sympathy for all these communities - no matter where they are and who they are.
Kyiv added that although he does not want to detail his views on the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, he certainly also supports the Palestinians, and noted that he has participated in many fundraising events for them over the past 20 years.
"But this is not a time for arguments, Achmat," clarified the singer, "It's a time to unite and support the Ukrainians, as a catastrophe is currently happening on their land."
I have great fans in Russia, and I know that many Russians strongly oppose Putin's regime actions.
"If I could play for them - I would do it."
In light of the decrease in morbidity: The Corona Projector will return to manage Ziv Hospital.
Prof. Salman Zarka was appointed to his position in July 2021 and led the policy for handling COVID-19 during the third and fourth waves.
At the request of Health Minister Nitzan Horowitz, he will continue in his role as a projector in parallel.
Prof. Zarka: "Glad that the Omicron wave continues to decline, but we still have a duty to prepare for another wave."
.
Against the backdrop of the decline in coronavirus morbidity, the coronavirus project manager, Prof. Salman Zarka, will return to manage Ziv Hospital in Safed on Sunday.
At the request of Health Minister Nitzan Horowitz, he will continue in his role as a projector.
"I am happy for the citizens of Israel that the Omicron wave continues to decline and that we have got our normal life back," said Prof. Zarka, adding: "We still have a duty to prepare for another wave of illness as a result of the virus still being here, in Israel and around the world."
Prof. Zarka was appointed to his position in July 2021 and led the policy for handling COVID-19 during the third and fourth waves.
Starting from May 1st, Israel has returned to a "between waves" state, which includes a maximum reduction of the Corona systems, while maintaining the ability to perform continuous tests and investigations, which will be the basis for action in case a new variant is detected.
Latent disease
In the report of the National Knowledge and Information Center for the Corona System, published this morning, it was noted that "there is a decrease in the average of new confirmed cases to below two thousand per day, in the weekly average, alongside a decrease in the number of hospitalized and severely ill patients."
However, they emphasized that "there is a significant amount of hidden morbidity and in reality, the number of infected people is much higher.
The number of institutional tests conducted in the community (excluding tests for returnees from abroad, etc.) is low, standing at less than 20,000 average weekly tests only.
The low volume of tests makes it difficult to identify disease trends and understand them.
State Comptroller's report: The actual budget for most years of the Drug Basket Committee's activity - is less than the recommended budget.
According to Netanyahu Engelman's report, for over 20 years of the basket's activity - the Ministry of Health did not supervise the committee's activity.
The report also states that the meeting protocols are published significantly late, if at all.
Also, the reviewer recommends increasing the transparency of the subcommittee's activities - and updating the basket's work procedures.
Another deficiency found relates to the fact that since the committee began its work, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds to report on the extent of use and utilization of the drugs in the basket - which would have allowed to analyze and control the budget given to them.
The Drug Basket Committee is one of the most influential public committees on our daily lives and our health.
Every year, the committee decides on new medications that will be provided to the public free of charge through the health funds - but a new report by the State Comptroller published today (Tuesday) warns that it has been operating for over 20 years without any control reports on its activity and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council supervising and examining its activity.
"Israel Today" writer, Ran Reznik, adds that the State Comptroller's investigation was conducted following the ongoing exposures in "Israel Today" about the failures of the drug basket.
According to Netanyahu Engelman's report, he recommends "to make amendments and improvements in the process of expanding the health services basket, which will lead to a better utilization of the health services budget that the public is entitled to."
Throughout the existence of the drug basket addition mechanism, from 1998 to 2021, drugs worth eight billion shekels were added to the state budget - with the addition varying each year in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels.
In the years 2019, 2020 and 2021, requests were submitted to add about 800 new drugs and technologies to the health services basket, with a total annual cost of more than two billion shekels.
In practice, the budget allocated for the expansion of the basket was smaller than the volume of requests.
During most of the committee's operation years (90% of the time), the increase in the budget was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired increase rate.
The reviewer suggests that there is a need to examine and regulate the annual increase in order to allow certainty and long-term planning.
Engelman also noted that "the transparency model in the basket's work is lacking".
For example, the work procedure of the Basket Committee stipulates that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, should be published within 60 days, but in practice, the minutes are published with a delay of 109-160 days, and sometimes the final meeting minutes are not published at all.
"The delay in publishing the protocols harms the transparency of the decisions; as a result, the ability of the proposal submitters - patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies - to submit repeat requests as soon as possible and relevantly may be impaired, after they have learned from the rejection of their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and corrected their proposals and conducted a renewed assessment of the likelihood of their acceptance in the next round," the auditor stated in the report.
"The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols according to the schedules set in the procedure."
Out of thousands of submissions - only one economic comment was submitted.
Another criticism by Engelman relates to the preliminary process of evaluating the technologies proposed for the drug basket.
The reviewer found that nearly half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for rejection.
Another deficiency relates to the subcommittee's activity on the drug basket, which is closed to the media and the public, and where the number of patients and the cost of drugs are discussed.
The reviewer recommends adding a public representative or examining the possibility of publishing the discussions to the public without private commercial details.
According to the procedure by which the Health Services Basket Committee operates, it is determined that "an economic assessment" must be submitted for a request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic assessment has been submitted out of thousands of submissions - and the committee makes its decisions without an economic assessment.
For example, for the 2019-2021 basket committee discussions, requests were submitted to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket.
The report revealed that economic assessments were not attached to the requests, including an estimate of the amount that could be saved by reducing damage from diseases caused by obesity or the ability to avoid gastric bypass surgeries.
It also appears that the decisions of the Drug Basket Committee do not align with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
For example, in 2019, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparation for treating the increase in chronic diseases as goals, but in the decisions regarding the expansion of the health basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The auditor also warns that since 2011, services that are not the responsibility of the health funds, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccines, provided by the Ministry of Health ("the third supplement"), have been included in the drug basket.
This, when the legal framework for this step is only arranged retrospectively.
In the last six years, 74 million shekels from the addition to the drug basket have been used for these services.
Engelman recommends the Ministry of Health to update the basket work procedures and also to determine whether there is a need for a separate financial supplement for these services.
A third of the new drugs added to the medicine basket are defined as "no additional cost drugs", which do not cost the health funds any additional amount because they replace an existing treatment.
The reviewer suggests examining the possibility that these drugs will be handled in a different and shorter track, so that the drug basket can be updated several times a year and not just once a year.
There is no supervision over the use of particularly expensive drugs.
The review also reveals that since the Basket Committee began its work 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds to report and has not supervised the extent of the use and utilization of the drugs in the basket, information that could have allowed the ministry to analyze and control the budget given to the funds.
Over the years, only two reports have been published that refer to the years 2006-2009, and even these were published with a noticeable delay (the last one was published this year and dealt with the budget utilization in the years 2007-2009).
"The delay in conducting tests may lead to difficulties in data collection and analysis, irrelevance of the conclusions drawn from the test after such a long period, suboptimal pricing of the subcommittee, and decisions based on preliminary findings," the report states.
Also, the office does not monitor and supervise the use of particularly expensive drugs and has not conducted a lesson learning process.
We are talking about 10 drugs that constituted 62% of the addition to the basket (1.7 billion shekels in the years 2021-2016).
Regarding this, the critic wrote: "It is recommended that the Ministry of Health conduct private inspections on these drugs and technologies and analyze the extent of their use compared to the estimates.
Audits and analysis will allow systemic conclusions to be drawn about the work process of the Basket Committee and the subcommittee, and about the method of preparing estimates when pricing drugs and technologies, and to improve them.
"Shocking and inconceivable": A heated debate in the Health Committee about the poisoning at Dafna's house.
The vital signs of the first patient who passed away were normal ten minutes before her death.
The committee chairman, MK Silman: "If people there cared that the kitchen would be like at home - it wouldn't look like this."
Ten minutes before the first victim, a 40-year-old woman from "Beit Dafna" in Holon, died from food poisoning, her medical measurements were taken and were normal, claimed the director of the institution today (Tuesday) at a health committee meeting.
"We have night caregivers who check during the night and a nurse who does rounds."
There were several reports of diarrhea and the last time the tenant had her vitals taken was 10 minutes before she stopped responding and they were normal.
She was tracking like the rest of the hikers with diarrhea.
She is under nursing care, we went to get a stretcher to assist with her transfer and then that tenant did not respond.
"We started resuscitation and called the nursing sister," described the home manager about what happened last Sunday morning at the home.
This is an event in which three residents died, six were hospitalized, and in total about a quarter of the home's residents (33 out of 131) suffered from diarrhea after eating contaminated meat.
The dormitory manager said these things against the backdrop of claims that death from food poisoning indicates neglect and lack of supervision by the caregivers.
Dr. Naama Nos, the epidemiologist in charge at the Tel Aviv Health Bureau, stated that "we cannot definitively determine what caused the three soldiers to pass away."
Only blood tests were taken from them.
It was also discussed that it was no longer possible to collect stool samples from the residents who were hospitalized because they did not defecate, therefore it was impossible to definitively determine the cause of death and illness.
The engineer from the Ministry of Health also noted that "The Ministry of Health checks the sanitary conditions in the kitchens of institutions once every four years at the request of the Ministry of Welfare or for the renewal of a license."
The Welfare Ministry admitted that an investigation committee has not yet been appointed for this case and for a previous case of abuse in shelters that occurred three months ago at the "Bnei Zion" institution in Sharon.
The Chair of the Health Committee, MK Idit Silman, said during the discussion: "If people cared that the kitchen would be like at home - it wouldn't look like this.
The residents in the welfare homes need more.
They are health sensitive and require extra supervision and care.
It's shocking and unbelievable what happened there.
The horrific findings were discovered only after they knew that the Ministry of Health was coming to inspect.
Where is the supervision and responsibility of the ministries?
How come the ministers and the directors of the departments are not present in such a discussion to provide an explanation about what is happening here?
Yigal Nachtomi, the CEO of Beit Eckstein who manages the home and even ran the home himself said "Hundreds and thousands of people in the entire system wake up with only one goal: to do good for people."
The people who passed away are people I personally cared for.
I put one of the tenants to sleep in my arms.
"It's a moving event for us."
Smadar Ona, a former resident of the same home at her age, burst out at him and said, "Enough with the lies and the pretty words."
"I was there."
Gali Barami, representative of the parents at Akim Israel: "We have complained about the food in the past and they did not accept the criticism."
Oren Helman, the founder of the Equal Chance initiative for integrating people with disabilities, protested that the names of the deceased victims were not published: "Their names are not known at all."
Are they worth less?
They belittle our children's lives".
Suspected negligence at Wolfson: The surgeon caused a tear in the heart - and the patient died.
This is the first procedure that Dr. Firas Abu Akar performed as the head of the chest surgery unit at the hospital.
The chairman of the doctors' committee complained that the director, Dr. Engel, was warned before his appointment.
In the hospital: "He is valued and experienced."
First published: A horrifying mistake occurred at the government hospital Wolfson in Holon, when during surgery the doctor caused a tear in the patient's heart, which led to his tragic death.
The surgery on the 83-year-old lung cancer patient was performed on April 19th.
This was the first surgery performed by Dr. Firas Abu Akar at the hospital, after being appointed as the head of the chest surgery unit at Wolfson.
During the surgery, which was intended to drain the area surrounding the patient's heart, the surgeon accidentally caused a large tear in the heart, leading to severe bleeding and resulting in the patient's death.
But the exceptional complication opened a Pandora's box, raising difficult questions about the hospital's management.
The director of the Oncology Institute and the chairman of the doctors' committee, Dr. Ronen Berner, demanded an investigation into the affair in a letter he sent to the hospital director, Dr. Anat Engel.
In the letter, he raised the most serious allegations about the conduct of Dr. Engel and the appointment of Dr. Abu Akar, this after the previous unit manager, Dr. Biny Zukerman, moved to Sheba Medical Center at Tel Hashomer.
A giant hole in the heart.
According to Dr. Berner's letter, the patient was lucid, functioning and treated by him in the last four years.
Recently, his disease has progressed, and an abnormal accumulation of fluids was discovered inside the pericardium, which contains the heart muscle.
Also, the surgeon Dr. Abu Akar, was under the impression that he could perform the surgery.
According to the complaint, a serious malfunction occurred during the surgery, and Dr. Hagai Dekel, head of the heart and chest surgery department at Wolfson, who was at the same time operating on a child in the adjacent room, "was hastily called to the operating table and saw a huge hole in the heart."
According to him, the heart was emptied of blood, the blood pressure was zero, and the surgical approach was wrong.
In addition, Dr. Berner reported that Dr. Dekel approached him and said that Dr. Abu Akar is not professionally and personally suitable to manage the chest surgery unit at Wolfson.
However, despite his explicit warnings and even though he was supposed to be the direct manager of the breast surgeon, Dr. Engel conducted a tender without involving him and appointed Dr. Abu Akar to the position.
He further noted: "It's a not complicated process that takes a few minutes," and added: "One cannot ignore the flawed process of Dr. Abu Akar's appointment to the position.
The question arises whether there is a direct responsibility of the surgeon for the failure of the surgery and the death of the patient.
Experienced surgeon.
In front of "Israel Today", information and claims from other senior doctors were raised that reinforce the questions raised by Dr. Ronen Barner in the case.
Dr. Mordechai Shimonov, head of Surgery A at Wolfson, responded to Berner's complaint and wrote that Dr. Abu Akar is "one of the most experienced surgeons in the country, but relatively young as a chest surgeon."
He added that he was chosen in a proper tender and Dr. Dekel did not participate in it, according to his statements about his desire to "disconnect" from the chest unit.
He also noted: "I was not part of the process either, and perhaps I should have been.
Dr. Shimonov wrote that Dr. Fras Abu Akar started working on April 10 and is entitled to 100 days of grace, "All the hospital doctors were impressed by his professionalism and his motivation and willingness to work.
He has already performed dozens of similar procedures, and unfortunately, the current case ended in a tragic way.
From Wolfson Hospital, it was responded: "We share the family's grief."
This is a patient of the oncologist Dr. Ronen Berner.
The chest surgeon mentioned in the article is a highly regarded and experienced surgeon, who was selected through a tender to manage the chest surgery unit affiliated with the surgery department at Wolfson Hospital.
According to Dr. Hagi Dekel, his quoted words are not accurate and were taken out of context.
It should be noted that unfortunately, the patient was in a very difficult condition.
The hospital is examining the case details transparently, and the Ministry of Health is aware of the case details.
