A model for healing: Three senior doctors talk about their mentors.
Prof. Galia Rahav misses the wit and wisdom of the late Prof. Marvin Shapiro, especially during the pandemic.
Dr. Shlomi Kodesh does not forget, even from his high position, the push from the late Prof. Saul Sokenik.
And Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev acknowledges Dr. Tomy Shinfield for the lesson in identifying with the patients.
Three key figures in hospitals write about those who inspired them and encouraged them to be better, both as caregivers and as human beings.
Three senior doctors, three life and profession teachers: On the occasion of Israeli Doctor's Day, "Israel Today" invited Prof. Galia Rahav, Dr. Shlomi Codish and Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev to recall the figures who accompanied them at the beginning of their journey - and helped them become who they are today.
Prof. Galia Rahav, head of the Infectious Diseases Unit at Sheba.
In memory of Prof. Marvin Shapiro.
The encounter that opened my eyes - and changed my life.
If I hadn't met Prof. Marvin Shapira, who was the head of the infectious diseases unit at Hadassah Hospital, I would probably have remained a specialist in internal medicine.
He is the one who made me love the field of infectious diseases and influenced me to pursue it.
I met him in the corridors of Hadassah, back in the 80s of the last century.
I never thought for a moment that I would leave internal medicine, as I loved treating the patient himself; but Prof. Shapira showed me that the field of infectious diseases is also expressed in neurology, internal medicine, and essentially in every area.
I thank him for bringing me into this field.
All along the way, I loved his investigative approach, an approach that gets to the root of the problem.
The discussions with him were analytical and logical.
He was a doctor in every fiber of his being, who loved his patients and taught me not to take anything for granted from them and to thoroughly examine everything.
He was a genuine and honest person, devoid of ego, qualities that I greatly admired in him.
At first, when I was asked to choose a doctor who was a role model for me and influenced me more than anyone else, I intended to choose my father, Dr. Yosef Rakover, a Holocaust survivor who served as a doctor in a partisan unit.
He was an amazing doctor, who influenced me to go into medicine - but he also reminds me of Marvin Shpira.
Both of them, for example, coined aphorisms that doctors still use today - such as "tissue is the issue", meaning, taking a biopsy of tissue from the affected organ allows to know which drugs should be given; or "when you use it, you lose it", which is meant to explain that overuse of antibiotics leads to bacteria becoming resistant to it.
The late Prof. Shapira was married to a physiotherapist who worked at Hadassah and was the father of two daughters.
He passed away about a year ago, and when I visited his family during the shiva, I cried.
He was something - a sharp and smart epidemiologist, who volunteered for everything.
He never complained, not even during his severe illness.
He was one of the first doctors on the team to treat epidemics, and he is greatly missed during this time.
If he was with us today, I'm sure I would have consulted with him, and I'm sure he would have been one of the team leaders in dealing with pandemics.
Published by: Mital Yassur Beit-Or
Dr. Shlomi Codish, director of Soroka Hospital.
About the late Prof. Shaul Sokenik.
A teacher and friend who supported me and raised generations of doctors.
.
I first met Prof. Saul Sockenik, of blessed memory, when I was a fourth-year medical student, and I came to do a rotation in internal medicine in the Internal Medicine D department that he managed.
Later, I returned to the department for a rotation in my sixth year, and I did my final project for medical school under his guidance, writing a computer simulation for a patient with polyarthritis (inflammation in multiple joints).
Saul has influenced every significant crossroad in my professional life over 20 years, and he was the most significant person in shaping my character as a doctor; not only professionally, but also - and mainly - personally and humanly.
During the internship, I was torn between family medicine and internal medicine, and I consulted with him about choosing the specialty.
Eventually, I chose to specialize in internal medicine at Soroka.
During my specialization, he provided me with constant guidance, in various aspects - in scientific writing (sorry Saul, I didn't persist enough), in dealing with patients, in working in a multi-professional team - an area in which the department excelled - and in fact, in every aspect related to medicine.
To this day, I identify in myself, as a doctor and a manager, characteristics that come from Saul.
When I finished my specialization and was unsure whether to go abroad for further training, Shaul pushed and guided me, and helped me with recommendation letters and advice on how to proceed.
The training period was a very important time for my professional development, and without Shaul's support and encouragement, I'm not sure it would have happened.
Upon my return, when I received an offer to join the hospital management, again Saul was the one who supported and assisted.
Later on, we went through complex periods together in the internal medicine department.
Saul knew how to wonderfully combine the roles of teacher, manager, friend, and team member, without any of his roles interfering with each other.
I aspire to succeed like him in this special combination.
He nurtured generations of students, interns, and specialists, who are now spread throughout the medical system in Israel, and their excellent work commemorates his memory and actions.
It is an honor for me to be appointed with this group.
Published by: Ilya Yegorov
Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev, Director of Schneider Children's Medical Center.
About Dr. Tommy Shinfield
The man who taught me medicine, and mainly listening.
Dr. Tommy Shinfield, the founder and former director of the Intensive Care Unit at Schneider Children's Medical Center, taught me to be an intensive care physician, but more than that - he taught me to think.
The inherent lesson I learned from him is to care for the most complex, the sickest children.
The children, who were healthy just a moment ago, are now between life and death.
The implicit meaning is to have very difficult, perhaps the most difficult, conversations with families who never imagined they would find themselves in these complex situations in the intensive care unit with their children.
It sounds strange, but it's self-explanatory.
But I learned even more significant and profound things from him.
Looking back, as a doctor who is a manager and a manager who is a doctor, I now clearly see the connection between the two worlds; the education I received from Dr. Shinfield bridges them.
Dr. Shinfield taught me to listen attentively to many things: to listen to the children, to the monitor, to the caring nurses, to both the young and old care teams, and to the parents.
All of this needs to be done not only to communicate more correctly and successfully, but also to constantly gather a lot of information that can prevent the next deterioration.
The preventive processes in treating children exist everywhere, and of course also in intensive care.
Listening and conversation foster a deeper understanding, both from the treatment team and from the patients and their families.
My understanding today as a manager is that these insights are also correct when looking at a whole system.
The more in-depth and meticulous understanding that involves all the caregivers in the conversation, the more accurate, situation-appropriate, and primarily, the decision-making process will be timely in order to prevent future, immediate or distant damages.
That's why Dr. Tommy Weinfeld is much more than an inspirational figure to me.
He is a person who taught me a lot about medicine, but mainly taught me to think quickly and accurately, to listen - and then to implement.
