Medical negligence at different stages of birth.
In order to win compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that the damage was caused by that negligence.
Birth is one of the most joyful and exciting events in a family's life.
However, unfortunately, sometimes births end in severe damages caused to the mother or the newborn as a result of the medical team's negligence.
In cases where the birth resulted in physical harm to the newborn or the mother, it is appropriate to examine the sequence of events that led to the injury and even consider seeking legal advice.
A lawyer specializing in medical negligence will examine whether there were flaws in the medical team's conduct during the various stages of birth that caused damage, and if deemed necessary, will consult with a medical expert in the relevant field.
It should be emphasized that not every mistake in treatment by the medical team amounts to negligence (in the legal sense of the term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily indicate that it was negligently managed.
When is it considered negligence?
When the doctor's mistake stemmed from a lack of skill or deviation from the reasonable level of caution, and the lack of skill and deviation from the accepted level of caution caused harm to the patient that would not have occurred had the doctor not acted in such a way.
In this article, we will examine the different stages of birth, explain the complications that may occur in each stage and when they amount to medical negligence.
The stage of axes.
The labor stage lasts on average between 8 to 14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix gradually opens (to allow the passage of the fetus during birth) and at the end of the process, it should reach a diameter of about ten centimeters.
Most cases of medical negligence during labor involve failure to identify fetal distress leading up to birth, which sometimes results in brain damage to the newborn.
Cerebral Palsy (CP):
Brain damage may occur as a result of failure to identify or delay in identifying sub-birth asphyxia, which is manifested by a failure in oxygen supply to the fetus's brain tissue.
Generally, monitoring the condition of the mother and correctly interpreting the monitor that tracks the fetal heart activity should lead to early identification of fetal distress, allowing the medical team to act quickly and deliver the baby before irreversible damage occurs.
Cases where the medical team ignores signs that the fetus is suffering from oxygen deficiency, or the team does not correctly interpret the data in front of them, particularly the fetal monitor, or responds late to the distress shown on the monitor - may constitute negligence.
Brain damage can also be caused as a result of umbilical cord prolapse and also as a result of an undetected uterine rupture.
Even in these difficult events, it is appropriate to investigate whether the medical team acted properly.
For example, Attorney Anna Reich Ligenza, from the Kaspie Seror & Co. law firm that specializes in representing victims of medical negligence, tells that her office handled a lawsuit of a child who was injured during his birth after the midwife ruptured the amniotic sac when the baby's head was too high, causing the umbilical cord to descend (when the umbilical cord precedes the baby's head) and damage to the oxygen supply to the baby's brain (as a result of the pressure of the baby's head on the umbilical cord), resulting in him being born with severe neurological damage.
In another case, the lawyer reported that her office filed a lawsuit due to severe medical negligence by a maternity ward team in a large hospital, which during the birth did not identify in time clear signs that the birthing woman was suffering from a tear in the uterus in the area of the surgical scar from her previous pregnancy.
The fetus, which escaped through a tear in its mother's womb into the abdominal cavity, suffered from severe fetal distress until it was rescued at a late stage when it was on the verge of death.
Due to the severe distress during his birth, the child suffered a complex neurological disability.
We emphasize that in order to be entitled to compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal link between the medical team's negligence that led to the failure to identify the complication and the damage caused to the newborn, meaning that the damage was caused due to the aforementioned negligence and not from any other reason or factor.
The examination of the causal link will be conducted by examining medical indices that, according to the medical literature, only when they occur there is a causal link between the asphyxiation and the brain injury.
Among other things, the fetus's blood acidity level, his Apgar scores, the presence of neurological and systemic injury, and more are examined.
The death of the fetus.
The active labor stage.
The active stage of labor begins when the cervix dilates to a diameter of 10 centimeters and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most of the medical complications occur during this critical stage.
Birth asphyxia and avoidance of performing a cesarean section.
In certain cases, a dysfunctional labor develops, meaning, a lack of progress in the active birth process.
In such cases, it is common to perform a cesarean section, in order to prevent various damages that might be caused to the fetus due to the delay in birth.
"There are cases where not performing a cesarean section on time could cause irreversible damage to the fetus," explained attorney Reif-Ligenza to us.
"For example, we handled a medical negligence lawsuit of a stillbirth caused by a significant delay in performing a cesarean section."
Contrary to all recognized medical practice, the medical team failed to identify the fetal distress and perform a cesarean section despite the particularly slow progress of the birth.
The delay in performing the surgery caused systemic damage to the mother, which eventually led to her death shortly after giving birth.
Negligence in childbirth and vacuum.
In situations where there is a significant risk to the mother or fetus that requires a particularly rapid end to the birth, a vacuum delivery (empty extractor) is sometimes performed.
In this process, a "cap" is attached to the fetus's head using a vacuum and the fetus is then pulled out with force.
Naturally, this action involves risks and may cause harm to both the passer and the birther, therefore it requires caution, precision and great skill.
In these events, medical negligence may be expressed in the doctor not adhering to mandatory guidelines and performing the procedure despite the existence of a contraindication, such as when the baby's head is too high in the pelvis, or performing it for a longer time than allowed, or when despite several failed attempts, the doctor continues and repeats the procedure more than the allowed number of attempts.
In these cases, if the negligent vacuum procedure caused damage - among other things, it could cause cranial damage and bleeding that could lead to brain damage - there is room for filing a lawsuit.
Silencing in the name of ERB.
Erb's palsy, a congenital nerve injury in the brachial plexus (the nerve junction connecting the spine to the upper part of the shoulder), when it occurs during birth, it is appropriate to check whether the damage was caused by negligence of the delivery team.
The injury manifests as weakness in the arm muscles and can lead to complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This silence is often caused by difficulty in delivering the baby due to 'shoulder dystocia' - an obstetric emergency that occurs when the baby's shoulders get stuck in the birth canal after its head has come out.
When should you suspect that the silence was caused by medical negligence?
In cases where the fetus's weight assessment indicated that it is macrosomic, meaning it is expected to be born weighing more than 4.5 kilograms, it is preferable according to guidelines to deliver the mother by cesarean section.
When the fetus weighs more than 4 kilograms, a cesarean section should be considered due to risk factors including gestational diabetes and the prolongation of the second stage of labor.
In the case that the medical team ignores the abnormal weight assessment of the fetus or other risk factors and chooses to proceed with vaginal birth, and the risk of shoulder dystocia and ERB's palsy occurs, there is a reasonable possibility that this is medical negligence.
Indeed, in case number 2694/90, the Supreme Court ruled that "the risk of shoulder dystocia during childbirth can be predicted with some degree of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder dystocia, where there is a risk of its occurrence, is to perform a cesarean section".
The stage of the placenta's expulsion.
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its expulsion occurs due to the contraction of the uterus after the birth of the baby and is accompanied by bleeding.
The process usually lasts up to half an hour from the moment the baby is born and according to many, it happens spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical team.
After the placenta is delivered, the medical team will check if it came out completely or if parts of it remained in the uterus.
During this stage, complications may occur that could cause serious harm to the mother.
One of the known complications resulting from the retention of placental remnants in the uterus is called "Asherman's syndrome", a scarring of the uterine wall caused by inflammation due to the retention of placental remnants in the uterus, a phenomenon that damages the uterine lining in a way that prevents pregnancy implantation.
Therefore, in cases where the medical team did not identify that placental remnants were left or did not take all measures to prevent damage to the uterine wall despite suspicion of placental remnants in the uterus, it may be a case of medical negligence and the case should be thoroughly examined by an experienced attorney in the field.
The death of the mother.
The death of a mother during childbirth is a rather rare event.
In these cases, the event that was supposed to bring joy and happiness to the entire family, unfortunately, turns into the most tragic event for them.
In certain cases, the medical team does not detect bleeding in the woman giving birth on time or responds late to such bleeding.
"For example...", Attorney Reich-Ligensa told us, "our office filed a lawsuit concerning the death of a mother during childbirth, where in that case the medical team ignored and did not respond to the alarming vital signs of the mother for many hours, and was late in diagnosing a massive and uncontrollable bleeding that occurred as a known complication of the underlying disease she suffered from."
"In another case...", attorney Reich-Ligenza reported, "our office represented the relatives of a woman who passed away after giving birth to twins due to bleeding that originated from a cesarean section incision that was not properly stitched."
In that case, the woman who gave birth complained about severe pain and weakness after the surgery, but the medical team did not properly address her complaints and her clinical condition, only responding with delay after her body systems began to collapse, which led to her death.
Loss of a uterus.
In severe cases, medical negligence during childbirth may lead to a hysterectomy, says attorney Reif Lingza: "Our office filed a lawsuit against a hospital based on a hysterectomy due to medical negligence after childbirth."
In that case, the mother, a young woman of 31, lost her uterus due to inadequate treatment of massive bleeding observed by the medical team after the birth, and yet timely actions that could have prevented the damage were not taken.
What are the compensations awarded in lawsuits for medical negligence during childbirth?
Compensation for birth injury due to medical negligence includes many components of damage, with the most significant amounts given for pain and suffering, nursing and treatment costs, loss of earnings and pension for the victim and even for his parents, and additional damage components.
The compensation awarded to a minor victim for loss of earnings and pension is calculated in most cases based on the average wage in the economy.
Also, the compensation includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitation equipment, the cost of adapting housing to the baby's needs, mobility, and more.
"The compensation amount is determined in each case individually and according to its circumstances," says attorney Reif-Ligenza, adding that "today, most medical negligence claims end in a compromise that balances the chance and risk each party has in conducting the process." However, she added and noted that "there are cases where the process only ends with a verdict, then if the claim is not dismissed, the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damages. For example, in a case handled by our office, the District Court awarded a minor who suffered brain damage due to a delay in identifying a transient ischemic attack, a compensation exceeding ten million shekels."
In conclusion
Medical negligence during childbirth is undoubtedly every family's nightmare.
In these cases, a correct legal examination of the chain of events that led to the tragic outcome, by a lawyer skilled in managing medical negligence claims, can help you win the compensation you deserve.
This is the reason for the prevalence of the eye disease Keratoconus in the south.
The research revealed that there is a connection between the development of the disease and close relatives.
The highest prevalence was found in the Bedouin sector.
Expert: "In any sector with many marriages between relatives, there may be a high prevalence of disease."
Keratoconus is a hereditary eye disease that causes several vision impairments.
It is very important to diagnose it as soon as possible, and to find the right solutions to prevent the situation from worsening.
In recent years, several studies have been conducted that help understand how the disease develops, and innovative treatments have been developed.
The new studies provide research basis for the suspicion that the eye disease Keratoconus is a genetic disease.
Recent research, which focused on the transformation of the cornea from a dome to a cone, revealed that the disease and weakness of the cornea and the distortion of its shape are related to an enzymatic imbalance, which can lead to free radicals damaging the proteins in the cornea - and its structure will change.
The lack of those enzymes is genetic, a fact that strengthens the assumption that keratoconus is a hereditary disease.
According to Prof. Ariela Gordon-Shaag, head of the Optometry Department at Hadassah Academic College, "In a study published among Arab students in Haifa, a prevalence of keratoconus was found to be 3.2%."
The highest prevalence was among Bedouin students - 20% had keratoconus, but the sample size was relatively small.
The researcher added that this is not a surprising finding: "There is a high prevalence of keratoconus in the Bedouin sector.
In our research, we found that close marriages are a risk factor for keratoconus disease.
Thus, in any sector with many cousin marriages, there may be a high prevalence.
In this context, it should be noted that this is an important finding given the unequivocal conclusion: in cases where there is a family history of keratoconus disease, all family members should undergo appropriate eye examination as soon as possible.
According to Erezah Fruchter, a clinical optometrist B.Sc, "There is a tenfold increase in referrals to the clinic from remote peripheral areas, mainly from the south, compared to the center."
Proctor adds that "In the last decade, I noticed that most of the patients come from the periphery, especially from the Be'er Sheva area."
This is mainly due to the high prevalence of marriages within the family (especially in the Bedouin sector) and various allergies, and a lack of awareness of the proper treatment of the problem.
So how is the disease diagnosed?
Proctor explains that keratoconus usually develops during adolescence or in the late teens (ages 15-16 or 20).
The disease involves a decrease in vision, along with an increase in cylinder.
People with keratoconus report distorted and/or blurred vision of figures and objects.
These symptoms worsen with the progression of the disease, which usually develops slowly and gradually over the years.
However, the disease can also progress rapidly and reach its peak within just a few months.
Many of the patients even report increased sensitivity to light.
