A senior police officer: "There is a need for government policy and setting goals."
Israel Police has indeed launched an operation to mitigate the phenomenon of illegal squatters, but the road is still long.
Today in Israel, there is not a single entity that encompasses this entire issue.
"If we want to address the issue of illegal immigrants, a government policy is required, from which goals, tasks and responsibilities should be derived.
"Today in Israel, there is not a single entity that encompasses this entire issue," a senior police officer tells "Israel Today".
Until a month and a half ago, before the escalation in the security situation, the phenomenon was manifested in about 20 to 30 thousand Palestinians entering every day through breaches in the fence.
In addition, between 100 to 110 thousand Palestinians with work permits enter Israel every day through 34 supervised crossings.
It should be noted that Palestinians have been employed in Israel since the end of the Six-Day War, and the number of permits in each sector is limited by a quota set by the state according to the security, economic, and political situation in Israel.
The permits are issued by the IDF through the Coordination and Liaison Administration.
In light of this, an illegal worker is not necessarily a Palestinian whose entry is forbidden due to criminal involvement or connection to attacks, but often they are Palestinians whose entry is denied because they do not meet the permitted quota.
It should be emphasized that those who carried out the attacks in Ariel, Dizengoff and Elad were indeed considered terrorists, but they were not under surveillance, as they had not previously committed any criminal offense that required security forces to monitor their movements.
"Therefore, their entry through the breaches in the fence is meaningless," says a senior security official, "anyone who wants to carry out an attack can enter the country through the supervised crossings, and there have been such cases in the past."
Thousands of arrests.
Following the attack in Elad and due to the increase in attack warnings, the police launched a large-scale operation to locate illegal residents.
By the end of the week, about 16,000 Sabbath observers were arrested.
Out of them, about 600 were investigated and criminal cases were opened against them, and about 200 were imprisoned.
According to the police prosecution policy, proceedings against illegal residents are only carried out against repeat offenders or people who repeatedly commit the same act (recidivists).
An illegal resident who is arrested for the first time is investigated, documented and returned to the territories.
Sometimes this repeats itself even for the second time, but only on the third time he is arrested, imprisoned and an indictment is filed against him for illegal stay.
According to the law, if an illegal resident is caught within a range of about 50 to 100 meters from either side of the separation fence, he is dealt with by the military prosecution.
According to data obtained by "Israel Today", it appears that in 2021, the police handled 40,010 illegal residents, infiltrators, and asylum seekers.
7,405 illegal residents were arrested and criminal cases were opened against 19,533.
The number of employers, drivers and complainants handled by the police in 2021 was 6,537.
469 were arrested, and criminal cases were opened against 5,640.
