Watch: This is how the police prepare to neutralize terrorists in a civilian population.
The Jerusalem Border Police inaugurated a new "Asaf" facility that simulates shooting in a crowded audience in response to the series of attacks that have occurred in recent months.
The Jerusalem Border Police's counter-terrorism guide: "The development provides a relevant response to attribution threats and simulates the reality on the ground".
A glimpse into the "Asaf" facility.
Preparing for the next attack: A series of terror attacks carried out in the spring by Palestinians and Israeli Arabs, in which 19 people were killed and about 70 civilians were injured, led the Border Guard to develop a unique technique that trains fighters to charge at terrorists within a civilian population and carry out shooting on the move.
"Israel Today" exposure: A glimpse into the "Asaf" facility.
The popular terror focuses on harming civilians and its goal is to undermine the sense of security needed for the proper conduct of civilian population's life.
The severe wave of attacks that occurred this year, with attacks in Be'er Sheva, Hadera, Bnei Brak, Ariel, Elad, and especially the one that occurred in early April on Dizengoff Street in the heart of Tel Aviv, by a terrorist embedded in the crowd, led the police to creative thinking in order to develop a tool that would enable training fighters to attack terrorists within a civilian population.
The thinking process was led by the Police Training Department and the Border Guard.
These were presented in a competition in the different police districts under the title "Commanders Leading Learning", where each district was required to develop means to improve the patrolling and combat skills of the fighters, police officers and commanders.
As part of the competition, and in response to the need for Border Police soldiers to practice shooting in motion and in such scenarios, Assaf Ben David, a counter-terrorism instructor for the Border Police in the Jerusalem envelope, developed the "Assaf Device", which consists of a dynamic target, connected to a telescopic rod on which a carrier can be attached to the instructor.
The instructor, who straps the target to his waist, can train the fighter standing in front of him by controlling and moving the target to different sides and ranges.
It should be noted that in recent years, Border Guard soldiers have dealt with many attacks in which the perpetrator is shooting and posing a threat while moving in areas crowded with innocent civilians.
"The Asaf Device", in its current version, is based on components and parts that are used in various fields.
For example, the telescopic pole that was upgraded and integrated into the device, was taken from the maintenance and cleaning field.
Using the device, it is possible to simulate shooting in motion within a civilian population towards a dynamic target while maintaining eye contact with the object, handling traffic stops, choosing a path of progress for selective shooting, including practicing the prevention of harm to uninvolved parties.
Brigadier General Asaf Ben David, after whom the facility is named, says: "The facility we developed is a breakthrough in training and educating soldiers and police officers."
The development provides a relevant response to attribution threats and simulates the reality on the ground.
The benefit of development versus the relatively low production cost gives us a significant advantage in competition."
