Research states: Zoom meetings harm creativity.
About 2,100 engineers and academics around the world were asked to develop solutions to the problem - some in video meetings, some in face-to-face meetings.
The result: a virtual meeting hinders creativity and out-of-the-box thinking.
The research leader at Columbia University: "Visual focus on the screen harms the process of idea creation".
Nachama Porta: There is no harm to the work productivity or critical thinking.
A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the impact of meetings via video applications on the creativity of the participants, compared to face-to-face meetings.
Unfortunately, it was found that creativity indeed suffers in virtual meetings through screens.
The research question - led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University - was whether remote meetings via computer maintain the creativity that exists in office brainstorming sessions, or if the level of creativity and free thinking decreases as a result of the distance.
The research itself began in 2016 but received a major boost during the two years of the coronavirus, during which many employees switched to working from home.
"People in a pleasant personal meeting in a room, using objects and using them for creative thinking," says Brooks.
"In a face-to-face meeting, on the other hand, the focus on maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative activity in the brain."
The visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
People are more focused on the video during interaction, which hinders the process of generating and expanding ideas.
The space is shrinking.
To examine the results of the experiment and to verify if they would repeat, they were tested twice - once at Columbia University and another time in real life - on engineers who knew each other from early acquaintance.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 staff members and students into two parts - in one, the participants were asked to meet personally and develop solutions to a problem, and in the second, they were asked to do so via a computer.
Simultaneously, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East, and South Asia were asked to similarly divide and solve a problem presented to them in a new way.
In both cases, a decrease in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking was found among those who met virtually via video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher who studies ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his opinion, during a thinking activity, people usually look at their surroundings to help generate ideas, whereas in a video meeting, the thinking is focused on the screen and does not expand in a way that allows creativity.
"When people are in the same room, they look around and see the space, which contains objects and situations that can evoke new associations in them.
On the other hand, the research shows that computer-mediated relationships change our attention so that we are more focused inward and on the screen, and this way reduces innovation and idea generation through looking at the environment and thinking outwardly.
There is no harm to critical thinking.
However, before rushing employees back to the office, the researchers note that "working via computer did not harm productivity itself nor people's critical thinking on innovative proposals, when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas."
In other words, the damage is only targeted at creativity and not at other forms of computer work.
Prof. Ellen Langer, a psychology professor at Harvard University, also supports the findings.
According to her, "there is a difference between mere creativity, like new uses for a frisbee (one of the research questions; ed) and work solutions.
It's also possible that when the employees are more relaxed after getting to know each other, or when they are working from home, creativity will indeed improve.
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson suggested a future study in which such meetings would be interrupted for thinking states and wandering around the room to see how this activity would affect the final outcome.
Also, Dr. Olson suggested that as a result of the study, only brainstorming meetings will return to work and generally he suggested not to panic from one study but to conduct further research in the field.
"I wouldn't want employees to be forced back and not be happy, that's a bigger harm," he says.
