By 2050: The world will lose 80% of the water available for agriculture.
A new global study predicts a significant decrease in the next 25 years.
The solution: Proper management of water reservoirs.
A new and disturbing study recently published in the journal Earth’s Future, predicts that by 2050 the amount of water available for agriculture will decrease by about 80% if the rate of water consumption and world population growth remain at their current trends.
In the research, in which scientists from all science agencies around the world participated, they summed up the total amount of rainwater, rivers and freshwater sources in the world and compared it to the needs of humanity in agriculture.
The grim conclusions of the research show that as of now, the rate of water consumption has been doubling again and again over the last 10 years, while global warming is causing a decrease in rainfall in agricultural areas around the world.
According to the research data, 84% of the world's agricultural lands will experience a severe shortage of rainfall.
One of the main conclusions from the research calls for farmers around the world to adapt their agriculture to climate changes and seasons, and to switch to cultivation methods that allow water to penetrate the soil in order to prevent the evaporation process that leads to a widespread waste of rainwater.
Also, the researchers recommend that farmers working near salty water sources use rainwater harvesting technologies to prevent their flow into the sea.
