Exempt from quarantine for vaccinated and recovered individuals from non-red countries, foreign tourists are returning.
Those who landed in the country received messages from the Ministry of Health stating that they are exempt from the quarantine obligation upon receiving a negative result for the Corona test.
Only after that, the ministry issued an official statement stating that it only applies to passengers from orange countries, despite the fact that returnees from red countries also reported receiving the message.
In addition: Tourists from orange destinations will be able to enter the country and many red destinations are expected to be removed from the list.
At the peak of the pandemic - is this the end of quarantine for those returning from abroad?
The Ministry of Health sent messages this morning (Monday) to those returning to the country, stating that they are exempt from quarantine upon receiving a negative result for the coronavirus test they took after landing in Israel.
This also includes those returning from red countries.
Some of the messages that were sent informed the returnees that they could be released after receiving a negative response or after 24 hours at the latest, and some of them received the exemption after they received the negative response.
Only after that, an official announcement was released by the Ministry of Health stating that starting from midnight on January 4, 2022, vaccinated or recovered individuals returning from red countries will undergo a PCR test at Ben Gurion Airport and will enter isolation for 24 hours or until a negative result is received (whichever comes first).
The decision will be marked in a directive from the Director General of the Ministry of Health and will be brought for approval to the Knesset's Health Committee.
The Ministry clarified that vaccinated or recovered individuals who have returned to Israel from a red country and received a negative result from the PCR test they took upon entering Israel, will end their quarantine at midnight and they are not required to take a second test.
Despite this, travelers from red countries reported that they also received the message.
Anyone who has not been vaccinated or recovered and returns from a red country, will enter home isolation for 14 days, with the possibility of shortening the isolation with a negative result of a PCR test conducted from the 7th day of landing in Israel (the day of landing is the first day).
The decision to lift most of the restrictions on flights, especially for the vaccinated, comes a day before the Supreme Court hearing filed by the Travel Agencies Association, the Open Skies Headquarters, and the Hotels Association.
In the discussion that will take place tomorrow, the petitioners are expected to demand the removal of all other red countries from the list, with Professor Itamar Grotto supporting them in his opinion.
Foreigners will also be able to enter.
The Prime Minister and the Ministers of Foreign Affairs, Health, Interior, Tourism, and Transportation have agreed that starting from Sunday, January 9, 2022, vaccinated/recovered foreigners (as defined by the Ministry of Health) from red countries will be allowed to enter, subject to filling out an online form in advance, performing a PCR or antigen test before boarding the plane, performing a PCR test upon entering Israel and then entering quarantine for 24 hours or receiving a negative test result (whichever comes first).
Non-vaccinated/non-recovered foreigners (according to the Ministry of Health's definition) will not be allowed to enter Israel.
Foreigners from red countries, except those whose entry has been approved by the Exceptions Committee, will not be allowed to enter Israel.
The group's plan will not be renewed at this stage.
And what about red countries?
The Committee for Country Classification at the Ministry of Health recommends to the government to remove the following countries from the red list and move them to the orange list: South Africa, Hungary, Nigeria, Spain, Portugal, France, Canada.
The countries that remain at this stage on the red list are: United Arab Emirates, USA, Ethiopia, United Kingdom, Tanzania, Mexico, Switzerland, and Turkey.
Another option that the Ministry of Health is considering is to exempt vaccinated individuals returning from red countries from quarantine.
Currently, it is unclear whether there is a connection between the messages received this morning by those returning to Israel and the guidelines that may be issued by the Ministry of Health on this matter.
No response has been received from the Ministry of Health yet.
The skies are starting to open: The Ministry of Health is changing the restrictions on the country's borders.
Vaccinated individuals returning from red countries will be required to quarantine for 24 hours.
The countries USA, Turkey, Britain and the United Arab Emirates will be defined as red.
After long weeks in which it was very difficult to find a destination to fly to without restrictions, and after all those returning from abroad were required to quarantine, alongside the ban on tourists entering Israel - yesterday it was decided to change the procedures and significantly ease the restrictions on Ben Gurion Airport.
The Ministry of Health has decided to recommend cancelling the three-day quarantine requirement for Israelis returning from red countries.
So far, anyone who is vaccinated or recovered according to the Ministry of Health's definitions and returned from a red country - is required to be in isolation for three days, subject to two corona tests.
Now, the quarantine that vaccinated and recovered individuals returning from red countries will have to enter is for 24 hours at most, or until they receive the results of the coronavirus tests conducted after landing at Ben Gurion Airport (whichever comes first).
Anyone who is not defined as vaccinated or recovered will still be required to enter seven days of isolation subject to two corona tests, or 14 days without the second test, whether returning from an orange country or a red country.
A vaccinated or recovered person returning from a red country is also required to be in full quarantine.
The updated list of red countries recommended by the Ministry of Health, which still needs government approval, includes the USA, Turkey, Tanzania, Ethiopia, Mexico, Britain, Switzerland, and the United Arab Emirates.
In all countries, except Turkey, the average of positives who entered the country in the last two weeks is more than 5% of all entrants, which automatically puts them on the red countries list.
The rate of increase among patients from Turkey is fast, the rate of positive returnees from it stands at just over 4%, and therefore it was decided to also include it in the list of red countries.
The prominent countries that were removed from the red list: France, Spain, Portugal, and Canada.
Starting from January 9, vaccinated tourists who meet the Ministry of Health's requirements will be able to enter Israel without the need for quarantine, similar to the conditions for Israelis returning from a red-listed country.
In this case too, the decision is subject to government approval, which will discuss the matter in the coming days.
It's important to note that there are few cases where the government does not approve the recommendations of the Ministry of Health in this field.
The tourists are against the restrictions.
The Travel Agencies Association, the Open Skies headquarters, and the Hotels Association have filed a petition to the Supreme Court to cancel the flight restrictions.
The country lifted most of the restrictions yesterday, but as mentioned, it left eight significant countries on the red list.
In the discussion that will take place this morning in Jerusalem, the petitioners are expected to demand the state to cancel the list of red countries.
The one who will support the petitioners' position is Prof. Itamar Grotto, who is expected to be present at the hearing.
The Minister of Tourism, Yoel Razvozov, who has supported easing restrictions on foreign tourists entering Israel in recent weeks, said yesterday: "Cancelling the quarantine for vaccinated returnees from abroad and resuming tourism for the vaccinated is the right and just thing to do at this time."
I am grateful to my government colleagues, who understood the crisis of the tourism industry and agreed with me that the damage outweighs the benefit.
The vaccine is the best response to the pandemic, and as such - the vaccinated public should be able to maintain a feasible lifestyle alongside the coronavirus.
